claim.claim-text:
1. A back pain relieving device for use by a person while the person is sitting or reclining comprising: 
(a) the back pain relieving device including a linear alignment support having at least two double pad supports mounted thereon; 
(b) the at least two double pad supports including at least a first double pad and a second double pad; 
(c) the first double pad having a central portion; 
(d) the central portion having a fastening device in order to secure the double pad to the linear alignment support; 
(e) the first double pad being similar to the second double pad; and 
(f) the first double pad and the second double pad cooperating with the linear alignment support to relieve back pain.

2. The back pain relieving device of claim 1 further comprising: 
(a) the at least two double pad supports including the first double pad, the second double pad, a third double pad and a fourth double pad; 
(b) the linear alignment support having the first double pad, the second double pad, the third double pad and the fourth double pad mounted thereon; 
(c) the linear alignment support having a top and a bottom; 
(d) the linear alignment support having the first double pad mounted at the top thereof with the second double pad, the third double pad and the fourth double pad proceeding sequentially on the alignment device; 
(e) the first double pad being larger than the second double pad; 
(f) the second double pad being larger than the third double pad; and 
(g) the third double pad being larger than the fourth double pad.

6. The back pain relieving device of claim 5 further comprising: 
(a) the at least two double pad supports having a durometer similar to that of skin in order to provide comfort to a user; 
(b) the first double pad having a first convex pad and a second convex pad; 
(c) the first convex pad and the second convex pad having a similar shape; and 
(d) the first convex pad and the second convex pad being on opposing sides of the linear alignment support.

16. A back pain relieving device for use by a person while the person is sitting or reclining comprising: 
(a) the back pain relieving device including a linear alignment support having at least two double pad supports mounted thereon; 
(b) the at least two double pad supports including at least a first double pad and a second double pad; 
(c) the first double pad having a central portion; 
(d) the central portion having a fastening device in order to secure the double pad to the linear alignment support; 
(e) the first double pad being similar in strcuture to the second double pad; and 
(f) the first double pad and the second double pad cooperating with the linear alignment support to relieve back pain.

17. The back pain relieving device of claim 16 further comprising: 
(a) the at least two double pad supports including the first double pad, the second double pad, a third double pad and a fourth double pad; 
(b) the linear alignment support having the first double pad, the second double pad, the third double pad and the fourth double pad mounted thereon; 
(c) the linear alignment support having a top and a bottom; 
(d) the linear alignment support having the first double pad mounted at the top thereof with the second double pad, the third double pad and the fourth double pad proceeding sequentially on the alignment device; 
(e) the first double pad being larger than the second double pad; 
(f) the second double pad being larger than the third double pad; and 
(g) the third double pad being larger than the fourth double pad.

18. The back pain relieving device of claim 17 further comprising: 
(a) the fastening device including a raised button; 
(b) the linear alignment support including a plurality of apertures centrally situated along a length of the linear alignment support; 
(c) a member of the plurality of apertures receiving the raised button; 
(d) the first double pad having a first convex pad and a second convex pad; 
(e) the first convex pad and the second convex pad being on opposing sides of the central portion; and 
(f) the at least two double pad supports being similar in structure.

19. A method of relieving back pain for use by a person while the person is sitting or reclining comprising: applying a back pain relieving device to a back of the person for a period of time and removing the back pain relieving device from the back when desired, the back relieving device having: 
(a) a linear alignment support having at least two double pad supports mounted thereon; 
(b) the at least two double pad supports including at least a first double pad and a second double pad; 
(c) the first double pad having a central portion; 
(d) the central portion having a fastening device in order to secure the double pad to the linear alignment support; 
(e) the first double pad being similar in strcuture to the second double pad; and 
(f) the first double pad and the second double pad cooperating with the linear alignment support to relieve back pain.

20. The method of claim 19 further comprising: 
(a) the at least two double pad supports including the first double pad, the second double pad, a third double pad and a fourth double pad; 
(b) the linear alignment support having the first double pad, the second double pad, the third double pad and the fourth double pad mounted thereon; 
(c) the linear alignment support having a top and a bottom; 
(d) the linear alignment support having the first double pad mounted at the top thereof with the second double pad, the third double pad and the fourth double pad proceeding sequentially on the alignment device; 
(e) the first double pad being larger than the second double pad; 
(f) the second double pad being larger than the third double pad; and 
(g) the third double pad being larger than the fourth double pad.
